Q13. Arduino Pin Types

# Arduino UNO Pin Types

| Pin Type       | Explanation                                                                                                               | Example                                                    | Real IoT Use Case                                                                            |
| ---------------| ------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- | ---------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| Digital Input  | Reads only two states: HIGH (1) or LOW (0).                                                                               | Push button or PIR motion sensor connected to pin 2.       | Detecting motion for a smart security system.                                                |
| Digital Output | Sends HIGH or LOW signals to control external devices.                                                                    | LED connected to pin 13.                                   | Turning a relay ON/OFF to control home appliances.                                           |
| Analog Input   | Reads analog voltage values (0–5 V) and converts them into digital values (0–1023).                                       | Potentiometer connected to A0.                             | Monitoring soil moisture or light intensity in smart agriculture.                            |
| PWM Output     | Produces Pulse Width Modulation signals to simulate analog output. Available on pins 3, 5, 6, 9, 10, and 11.              | Fading an LED or controlling a servo motor.                | Adjusting the brightness of smart street lights or controlling fan speed.                    |
| I2C / SPI Pins | Communication pins used to connect sensors and modules. I2C uses SDA (A4) and SCL (A5); SPI uses pins 10, 11, 12, and 13. | OLED display, RTC module, SD card module, or Wi-Fi module. | Connecting multiple sensors and displays in a smart home or environmental monitoring system. |
